<h2>North Carolina Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>North Carolina offers a comprehensive portfolio of incentives and rebates that significantly improve the economics of solar panel and HVAC system investments, starting with the federal 30% Investment Tax Credit (ITC) that applies to solar installations through 2032. This credit allows homeowners to deduct 30% of their total solar system cost, including equipment, installation, and permitting fees, directly from their federal tax liability. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, this translates to \$6,000 in tax credits, substantially reducing the net investment and improving payback periods.</p>

<p>The state provides additional support through North Carolina's property tax exemption for solar energy systems, which ensures that adding solar panels to your home will not increase your property tax assessment despite potentially increasing your home's market value by 3-4%. This exemption applies to both the solar panels and associated equipment such as inverters, mounting systems, and battery storage, providing ongoing tax savings throughout the system's 25+ year lifespan. Additionally, solar equipment purchases are exempt from North Carolina's state sales tax, reducing upfront system costs by an additional 4.75-7.5% depending on local tax rates.</p>

<p>Duke Energy offers several programs that benefit both solar and HVAC customers, including net metering for solar installations that allows homeowners to receive retail rate credits for excess electricity fed back into the grid. The utility also provides rebates for ENERGY STAR certified heat pumps and air conditioning systems through their energy efficiency programs, with typical rebates ranging from \$150-\$600 depending on system efficiency and size. Duke Energy's Smart Saver Programs offer additional incentives for smart thermostats, duct sealing services, and whole-home energy efficiency improvements, while their time-of-use rate schedules can provide additional savings for customers who can shift electricity consumption to off-peak hours using programmable systems.</p>

<p>Local municipalities throughout North Carolina offer additional incentives, with cities like Charlotte, Raleigh, and Asheville providing streamlined permitting processes for solar installations and some offering local rebate programs. Many counties participate in Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) financing programs that allow homeowners to finance solar and energy efficiency improvements through their property tax bills, spreading costs over 15-20 years while keeping payments with the property if sold. These combined federal, state, utility, and local incentives can reduce the total cost of solar installations by 35-45% and HVAC upgrades by 15-25%, making North Carolina one of the most financially attractive states for renewable energy and efficiency investments.</p>

